# React Frontend Standards

## Stack

- Use React with TypeScript for all UI code.
- Style with Tailwind CSS utility classes.
- Prefer shadcn/ui components (`Button`, `Card`, `Dialog`, etc.) when they fit the use case.

## Components

- Keep components small, focused, and reusable.
- Use named exports for components.
- Extract repeated UI patterns into shared components instead of duplicating markup.
- Success or error message should display inside a proper shadcn/ui components.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — default export, inline fetch, no states
export default function Page() {
  const [data, setData] = useState(null);
  useEffect(() => { fetch("/api/products").then(r => r.json()).then(setData); }, []);
  return data?.map(p => <div>{p.name}</div>);
}

// ✅ GOOD — named export, hook for data, explicit states
export function ProductList() {
  const { products, isLoading, error } = useProducts();
  if (isLoading) return <ProductListSkeleton />;
  if (error) return <ErrorState message={error.message} />;
  if (!products.length) return <EmptyState title="No products yet" />;
  return products.map((p) => <ProductCard key={p.id} product={p} />);
}
```

## Data Fetching

- Put API calls in `services/` or custom hooks (`hooks/`), not directly in page components.
- Pages compose components and wire hooks; they should not contain fetch logic.

## UI States

- Every data-driven view must handle loading, empty, and error states.
- Reuse shared state components (`ErrorState`, `EmptyState`, skeletons) when available.

## Naming

- Use clear, domain-specific component names: `ProductCard`, `ListingForm`, `ChatWindow`, `OfferPanel`.

## Responsive Layout

- Design for desktop and mobile using Tailwind responsive prefixes (`sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`).
- Test layouts at common breakpoints; avoid fixed widths that break on small screens.
